  "notes": {
    "greeting": "For You, Pooya",
    "cards": [
      {
        "icon": "🔄",
        "title": "What Changed and Why",
        "body": "Cycle 2 shifts from building strength foundations to driving hypertrophy through higher rep ranges, shorter rest periods, and greater training density. Rep ranges on compounds have moved from 6–8 to 8–12. Rest periods have dropped from 120–180s to 90–120s on compounds and 45–60s on accessories. Conventional deadlift has been removed — RDL covers your hinge pattern more effectively for muscle growth. Assisted pull-up has been replaced with lat pulldown, which gives you a more honest load to progress with at your current pulling strength. Each change responds directly to what we learned from your first five weeks."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🦵",
        "title": "Lower Body Is Still Catching Up",
        "body": "Your legs responded well to the adjusted volume in Cycle 1, but your lower body training age is still well behind your upper body. Squat at 50 kg and deadlift at 50 kg for an 88 kg male tells us these muscles are still in early adaptation. This cycle restores full set counts on lower body compounds but keeps eccentrics at 2 seconds rather than 3 to manage muscle damage. Do not chase heavy weight on legs — chase perfect reps at moderate load. The strength will come from consistency, not from one heroic session."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🎯",
        "title": "Shorter Rest Means Lower Weight — That Is the Point",
        "body": "When rest drops from 3 minutes to 90 seconds on bench press, you will not be able to use the same weight. That is expected and correct. The goal in this cycle is not to lift the heaviest load possible — it is to accumulate more total work in the same time window. If you find yourself resting longer than prescribed to maintain your Cycle 1 weights, you are missing the point. Drop the load 10–15% from where you ended Cycle 1 and respect the rest periods."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🍽️",
        "title": "The Deficit Conversation",
        "body": "You gained 2 kg in Cycle 1 — from 86 to 88 kg. You feel bigger and stronger, which is great, but visible abs require fat loss, and fat loss requires a caloric deficit that was likely not present in Cycle 1. This cycle is where nutrition needs to tighten. Target 1.8–2.0 g/kg protein daily (160–175 g) and aim for a weekly weight average that trends downward by 0.3–0.5 kg. If your weight is still climbing after two weeks, reduce daily intake by 200–300 kcal."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🎾",
        "title": "Tennis Is Fine — Nothing Else",
        "body": "One tennis session per week is manageable alongside this programme. Do not add boxing, extra cardio, or pickup games on top. Your near-fainting episode in Cycle 1 was your body telling you that the total energy demand exceeded your recovery capacity while in a deficit. If you want to add another activity, we remove a gym session to make room. Four gym days plus tennis is your ceiling this cycle."
      },
      {
        "icon": "📈",
        "title": "Progression Rules for This Cycle",
        "body": "Compounds — bench, squat, row, RDL, lat pulldown: when you can complete the top end of the rep range on all sets at the prescribed RPE, add 2.5 kg next session. Accessories and isolation — flies, curls, raises, extensions: add 1–2 reps per set before increasing load. Core exercises: add reps or extend the hold before adding external load. Log every session — the weights you record now determine your Cycle 3 starting point."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🧱",
        "title": "Core Is Progressing — Stay Patient",
        "body": "Stability ball rollout replaces dead bug as your primary anti-extension movement this cycle. This is a genuine progression — the unstable surface and longer lever arm demand significantly more from your deep abdominals. If you cannot maintain a rigid torso through the full range, shorten the rollout distance rather than letting your back arch. Cable crunch returns this cycle now that your core foundation is stronger. Focus on curling the ribcage toward the pelvis, not pulling with your arms. The ab work across four sessions per week is a high dose — do not add more on rest days."
      }
    ]
  }
